Build 'universal' binary wheels on macOS (#213)

The CI macOS machines are x86_64 architecture, but still support creating 'universal' binaries that will run on both x86_64 and arm64 architecture.
This PR:

    Adds macOS-specific patches for btor2tools, cadical, and lingeling to produce universal-binary libraries, following the recipe from the libgmp forum
    Changes CI for macOS to configure Boolector to produce universal binaries

The bulk of the changes are to add patch files to enable adding the '-arch' option to builds for the contrib projects, and updates to the scripts to build for both architectures and combine the resulting libraries to produce a universal library.

Signed-off-by: Matthew Ballance <matt.ballance@gmail.com>

Python: Only use repaired wheels as artifacts (#199)

The Python bdist (wheel) build process produces wheels named e.g.
`PyBoolector-3.2.2.20220630.7-cp39-cp39-linux_ppc64le.whl`. These
wheels are then "repaired" (libraries are bundled) by auditwheel
to produce files like
`PyBoolector-3.2.2.20220630.7-cp39-cp39-manylinux_2_17_ppc64le.manylinux2014_ppc64le.whl`.

In our previous build process, we had the original linux_ and the repaired
manylinux_ wheels in the same directory, and hence tried to upload both
to PyPi. This upload failed with an error message from PyPi:

```
ERROR    HTTPError: 400 Bad Request from https://upload.pypi.org/legacy/
         Binary wheel
         'PyBoolector-3.2.2.20220701.1-cp310-cp310-linux_ppc64le.whl' has an
         unsupported platform tag 'linux_ppc64le'.
```

Fix the problem by only placing the repaired wheels into the Azure
Pipelines build artifacts, and hence only uploading those files.

Signed-off-by: Philipp Wagner <phw@ibm.com>

commit.message:
CI: Small fixes for PyPi builds and uploads (#198)

* CI: Install twine where it is needed

Twine is needed in the upload step (from which it was
missing), but not during the macOS build.

Signed-off-by: Philipp Wagner <phw@ibm.com>

* CI: Only attempt PyPi upload if the build was successful

Signed-off-by: Philipp Wagner <phw@ibm.com>

* Build wheels only for specified Python versions

Right now, the Azure Pipelines base image contains a pre-release
version of Python 3.11, which we cannot build wheels for, or auditwheel
will fail. Exclude this version from the builds (since we don't want
to upload wheels for pre-release versions of Python either).

Signed-off-by: Philipp Wagner <phw@ibm.com>

commit.message:
Build ppc64le wheels for Python bindings

ppc64le is (today's) default PowerPC variant used with Linux and supported
by all large Linux distributions, including RHEL and SLES. Build binary
wheels of Pyboolector for this platform.

ppc64le support is not available natively in Azure Pipelines. To work around
that we use Qemu, which emulates a ppc64le environment on x86_64. This
approach is rather common so that "packaged" setup routines exist. In that
case, Docker is used to modify the host environment (odd, but it works) to
setup a binfmt handler for ppc to go through Qemu.

Signed-off-by: Philipp Wagner <phw@ibm.com>

Refactor and simplify PyPi builds

Refactor the Azure Pipelines description to make it easier to add further platform builds.

* Remove the Dockerfile, the build script can be called from the
  unchanged manylinux Docker image directly.
* Only install twine in the upload job, it's not needed in other places.
* Publish wheels as Azure Pipelines build artifacts.
* Collect all artifacts at the end, and upload them in one go.

Signed-off-by: Philipp Wagner <phw@ibm.com>

contrib/setup-utils.sh: Recognize 64-bit MinGW (#181)

On 64-bit versions of MinGW, `uname -s` will output:

```
$ uname -s
MINGW64_NT-10.0-19044
```

This trips up the `is_windows` function in `contrib/setup-utils.sh`, however,
as it only checks for `MINGW32*`, not `MINGW64*`. As a result, trying to build
`boolector` with 64-bit MinGW will fail since the proper Windows-specific
patches are not applied.

This provides a simple fix of checking both `MINGW32*` and `MINGW64*`.

Signed-off-by: Ryan Scott <ryan.gl.scott@gmail.com>
